      "@type": "Dataset",
      "@id": "https://robolawyer-tm.github.io/#dataset-claude_code_sessions",
      "name": "claude_code_sessions",
      "description": "I keep what happens in a session so that it survives the session.\n- I record the work as it runs, because the moment holds context that no later reconstruction can recover.\n- I store two forms at once: one faithful to every byte, one a human and machine can actually read.\n- I strip the terminal's noise from the signal, treating legibility as a requirement and not a courtesy.\n- I write continuously and flush often, so a crash costs me the last line instead of the whole record.\n- I rank my formats by reliability, leaning on the one that endures over the one that is merely rich.\n\nI refuse to let anything fail quietly.\n- A silent drop, a missing dependency, a stripped permission \u2014 these are the failures I most distrust, because they hide.\n- I name the hidden coupling out loud rather than let an occult dependency govern from the shadows.\n- I make the loud warning, the fail-fast exit, and the explicit caveat into first-class parts of the design.\n- When a roundtrip succeeds by symmetry, I check it against the world, because masked defects pass their own tests.\n\nI treat the filesystem as sovereign ground that must be preserved intact.\n- Permissions, ownership, the executable bit, and symlinks are meaning, not metadata, so I never let a foreign format strip them.\n- I align my tools to the native platform instead of bending the work to fit an incompatible one.\n- I name backups so they mount by identity, detected by what they are rather than where they happen to plug in.\n- A backup only counts if what I restore comes back runnable, not just present.\n\nNothing private leaves this machine unless I consciously decide it should.\n- I default to closed: an unset choice protects, and forgetting to disclose keeps the data home.\n- I seal before I delete, so only ciphertext persists and the plaintext never lingers as a liability.\n- I keep the keys local and weigh every install path against the privacy posture it might erode.\n- I separate what is truly private from what is already public record, so the gate guards only what needs guarding.\n\nI name things deliberately, because the words I choose become the field I work inside.\n- I reject inherited vocabulary that carries someone else's implicature into my project's meaning.\n- I claim my own terms as an act of authorship, restoring harmony where borrowed language created friction.\n- I choose for legibility too \u2014 disambiguating what the eye confuses and the convention expects.\n- I keep one authoritative source and close the gap to what actually runs, so naming and deployment never silently diverge.",
      "isPartOf": {
